<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-the-derivative">
  <title>The derivative</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Understand and apply linearity properties of the derivative.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Differentiate constant, linear, and power functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Combine linearity with product rules to differentiate polynomials.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Given a function <m>f</m>, we now know how to find its sensitivity at any point. We can use this to derive a new function <m>f'(x)</m> such that <m>f'(a)</m> gives the sensitivity of <m>f</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>. This new function is called the <term>derivative</term> of <m>f</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In differential form:
        <md>
          <mrow>\dv{y}{x} \amp = f'(x)</mrow>
          <mrow>\dd{y} \amp = f'(x)\dd{x}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        We <sq>should believe</sq> that if <m>y=mx+b</m>, then
        <md>
          <mrow>\dv{y}{x} \amp = m</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f</m> changes by a small amount <m>\dd{f}</m> and <m>g</m> changes by a small amount <m>\dd{g}</m>, we should expect the linearity properties to hold:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\dd(u+v) \amp = \dd{u}+\dd{v}</mrow>
        <mrow>\dd(cu) \amp = c\dd{u}</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Derivative of <m>x^2</m> can be done by visualizing a square of side length <m>x</m> and seeing how the area changes as <m>x</m> changes. You get two rectangles of area <m>x\dd{x}</m> and a small square of area <m>(\dd{x})^2</m>, which is <sq>negligible</sq>, so the total change in area is approximately <m>2x\dd{x}</m>, and we imagine that if the change were infinitesimal, the change in area would be exactly <m>2x\dd{x}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We can temporarily justify this sense of being <sq>negligible</sq> by looking at the <em>ratios</em> of changes:
            <me>
                \dfrac{\Delta(x^2)}{\Delta x} = 2x + \Delta x
            </me>
            If we imagine that <m>\Delta x</m> becomes infinitesimal, the second term drops out, so we say that <m>\DS\dv{(x^2)}{x} = 2x</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We'll make this sense of <sq>negligibility</sq> much more precise later when we introduce limits, but for now, we can just rely on intuition and the idea that if <m>\dd{x}</m> is very small, then <m>(\dd{x})^2</m> is even smaller and can be ignored.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Same thing can be done with <m>x^3</m>, by visualizing a cube of side length <m>x</m> and seeing how the volume changes as <m>x</m> changes. You get three rectangular boxes of volume <m>x^2\dd{x}</m> and three rectangular boxes of volume <m>x(\dd{x})^2</m> and a small cube of volume <m>(\dd{x})^3</m>. The higher powers of <m>\dd{x}</m> are <sq>negligible</sq>, so the total change in volume is approximately <m>3x^2\dd{x}</m>, and we imagine that if the change were infinitesimal, the change in volume would be exactly <m>3x^2\dd{x}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Power Rule (as a conjecture right now):
        <me>
          \dd(x^{n})=nx^{n-1}\dd{x}
        </me>
        (Only works when <m>n</m> is a natural number so far)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Derivative of a polynomial term by term... can verify the derivative done last section! If <m>L(v)=0.0034v^2 + 0.15v</m>, then
        <me>
            \dv{L}{v}=0.0068v+0.15
        </me>,
        so <m>L'(50)=0.0068\cdot 50 + 0.15=0.49</m>, which is the same as the slope of the tangent line we found last section. But it's much more direct and efficient.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

